metadata.name: Platonics #17
metadata.description:
A response to being buffeted by forces outside of our control. Platonics sought to find order, control and solace in the Platonic solids. Instead it found beauty and intrigue in the emergent chaos that can arise from even the simplest systems.

Its building blocks are the five Platonic solids. Forms which have fascinated humanity for thousands of years. Their title comes from the philosophy of Plato, who equated each of the solids with a classical element.

Platonics arranges these forms in a series of geometric layouts, with varying density and randomness. At one extreme we see tidy radial circles consisting of a single solid. At the other, packed pentagons consisting of jumbled solids give rise to Escher-esque compositions which hold near infinite variety, variety enhanced by a range of pens and colours that draw and fill those solids.

This relationship between order and disorder is at the heart of Platonics. The collection seeks to show how they are not so far removed from one another â and how we might embrace them both. It also aims to give collectors a behind the scenes look at how generative compositions can be constructed.

The geometric proof that there are only five convex regular polyhedra (the Platonic solids) states that at each vertex of the solid the angles between adjacent sides must be less than 360 degrees. This amount less than 360 degrees is known as the defect angle.

It is from this geometric proof that the collection size and pricing for Platonics is derived. There will be 360 Platonics sold via a Dutch auction priced according to the defect angles of the five Platonic solids: 180 > 120 > 90 > 60 > 36.

https://www.phaust.art/platonics

----------

Competition: Submit your favourite previews via Twitter to win a free mint and print.

Prints: Free gallery-grade, signed A3 prints for the first 18 mints.

Live: Press âSâ to save in hi-res or append '&size=#' to the URL for custom height.

metadata.name: The Streamline #134
metadata.description:
Form, an essential aspect in architectural design, refers to the shape, structure and arrangement of spaces or objects. Witnessing how forms work in a space can also be a transcendental experience, where one can sense the presence of a form, not only seeing it.

As there are many ways to create it, Form can appear as an internal structure, as an external shape of a two dimensional plane that envelopes a three dimensional mass, or a repetition of a two dimensional shape that stacks on an axis and moves to a certain direction. With so many ways to create shape, there is no law dictating that shape has to be rigid. And this is where Milunic and Gehry's design for the Dancing House comes in as an inspiration for this work.

A change in the political axis from one of a regime to a parliamentary democracy was what influenced the architects to juxtapose two different energies together. With its dynamic and static shapes in tandem, Dancing House is one iconic proof that form can also be pliable and animated.

metadata.description:
Notes: GPU intensive. May not render on some mobile devices. Renders fastest with Chrome.

Controls:
Press âsâ to save .png
Press 1-4 to change resolution:
1 - 1000px * 1410px
2 - 2000px * 2820px 
3 - 3000px * 4230px
4 - 4000px * 5640px 

Default resolution is 1000px * 1410px. It is recommended to explore in 2000px * 2820px or above.

Paleterum (latin âplateâ, âboardâ) â a flat surface that is used by artists to hold and mix colors.
This artwork is an attempt to simulate the look of watercolor on paper. Inspired by childhood memories that passed through the watercolor sketches of my mother, who was an artist, the piece reflects my admiration for her work and her influence on my own artistic endeavors. 
Intricate forms contrast with the strict forms of cells. All these are echoes from childhood - watercolor lines of a child not bothered by a special artistic idea but trying at least to a fraction of mastering the fine arts and cubes reminiscent of ones which children use to build towers.
Overall, the piece is a tribute to the joy and creativity of childhood, and to the power of artistic inspiration that can be passed down from one generation to the next.

Made with p5js and a few GLSL shaders.

metadata.name: Vorticity #55
metadata.description:
Vorticity is a gpu-accelerated flow field. The particles in the flow field orbit around a set of points that move around over time.

Controls: Click and drag to push particles away. Press the space bar to pause the simulation, and again to resume. While paused, you can press "n" to advance the simulation a single step. Press "r" to restart the simulation (if you change the resolution of the screen after the page loads, you will need to restart to update the resolution).

metadata.name: Mandelroid #542
metadata.description:
The Mandelbrot set is a mathematical object that is generated by a simple formula, and it exhibits some interesting visual patterns that are reminiscent of those found in nature, such as the self-similarity of branching structures, the repetition of small-scale patterns on larger scales, and the presence of chaotic behavior.

The beauty of Polaroid film lies in its ability to capture and preserve a moment in space and time in a unique and tangible way.

This work combines two things that are incongruent with each other and brings them together to create a digital memory that serves as a reminder that complexity can be found even in the simplest things, that art is intrinsic to nature itself.

metadata.name: Constellation Of Happiness #131
metadata.description:
Constellation Of Happiness is a collaborative art project between NFT artists Kato Trofimova and Andrew Erickson.

Feeling happy is tough this year but it'll be much easier when you get your own constellation of happiness! Using expressionistic code art, Constellation Of Happiness channels the purest festive emotions a person can experience, for example, when tasting champagne bubbles or seeing and touching confetti. All these are turned into beautiful constellations of happiness using the aesthetics of star maps and carefully brought to your NFT collection.

2022

Kato Trofimova (Latvia) is an illustrator, visual artist, and creative director known for her love of minimalistic shapes and bright palettes. In her art, Kato questions boundaries between styles and stays optimistic no matter what.

Andrew Erickson (Switzerland) is a generative artist experimenting with various abstract styles. Be it delicate monochromatic line art or colorful gradient minimalism, Andrew is very good at coding any kind of digital beauty.

metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #233
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, Iâm always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. Thereâs something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

metadata.name: ÃSSERS #9
metadata.description:
Human beings, living beings, existences.

Made of the same fundamental matter, instincts and drives.
The same basic frailties, hopes and dreams.

Meanwhile, we manage to shine in our own way. 
We build our own voice, particular, unrepeatable.
We cast a light, and a shadow, just like no other.

Swinging between these two realities we dance, 
playing the game of joining and splitting.

-

"ÃSSERS" attempts to suggest and evocate this dynamic equilibrium.
Basic colors, shapes and compositions that, despite being fundamentally the same, reclaim their distinctive identity and temperament.

-

Key features:

- 12 color palettes + background color
- 3 Symmetry levels
- 3 Vertex distribution modes
- # of polygons
- # of grid subdivisions

Secondary features provide additional variation.

metadata.name: Flexibility #4
metadata.description:
A circular composition made with the p5.js Perlin Noise. Polar coordinates are used in order to obtain the silk-like texture sometimes induced by the work.

From random numbers and trigonometry, this work has came to life and will help others to have a better life for themselves: 10% from primary + 10% from secondary will go to the Cure Parkinson's medical research.

Hope you admire this work as much as I do,

Carlz, 2023
